No name Thursday feature!  Simply stunning. 💫 Thanks for tagging #archi_ologie Posted @withregram • @doorwaysofchicago 🏠
➕WORKERS COTTAGE WEDNESDAY➕
📍N. Lincoln Park West - Oldtown Triangle

Although it looks like a workers cottage, what you'll discover on my Oldtown Triangle Walking Tour is that this is the only original farmhouse standing from when this area was still all farmland in the mid to late 1800's!

Learn about this and tons of other fascinating pieces of Chicago history, plus see over 40 of these darling workers cottages by coming along on my tour…click the link in my bio for tickets…4 different dates left for July! 

Leave a comment or message me with questions.

"Why not? "Wednesday 
If this were my cottage I might never leave home. In love 😍
Thanks for tagging #archi_ologie 
 Reposted from @the_onlycookiemonster Scotch eggs 

Having spent an evening drinking in a pub in a nearby village, missing their taxi home before falling asleep in a field only to wake up lost and soaked as it rained in the night, Mole, Ratty, Badger and Toad were relieved to be finally home after a four and a half hour walk around the countryside. 
“I told you those shots were a bad idea!” Said Ratty whilst trying to pull various seeds and grass out of Badgers fur. 
“We had Shots?” Asked Toad whilst watching Mole slowly wonder around the kitchen with a glass of water in hand whilst looking in a sorry state. 
“I have no idea!, I’m far more concerned on where all our clothes have gone and how we all ended up wearing Sombreros and hula skirts!” Said Badger.

Happy Wednesday aka hump day.. today we find ourselves with a bottle of water in hand loitering the wonderful streets of a beautiful village called Miserden in the Cotswolds.. Sunday Funday
The most fabulous home! 🖤🤍
I am obsessed with the trim work and the black and white! 
Thanks for sharing with #archi_ologie 
Repost @frenchallenhouse
News article from the year there home was built.
“Dorr O. French will soon erect a fine new home on Stuart Avenue” - Kalamazoo Gazette February 1895 

Dorr O. French, a prominent Lawyer and Justice of the Peace, built this Queen Anne Victorian in 1895. Marshall Field of Chicago supervised the interior decoration, putting emphasis on stained glass, butternut mouldings, ornamental plaster work, and even sending artists to paint a forest scene mural in the dining room, which is still preserved to this day. French lived here with his wife Emma and 5 children, until his death in 1919. Harold B. Allen, lead Statistician for Upjohn Company, took residency in 1928, and lived here with his wife Ethel and 3 children for 55 years, until his death in 1983.
